Tom makes a good point. I do not think &quot;ethnography&quot; had much to do with the conduct of the Vietnam War as fought by the troops.<br><br>
You also said:<br><br>
&quot;Vietnamese were looked at as less than equal<br>
 and this created the foundation for the dehumanization<br>
 of the enemy and the ability for people to consider<br>
 and perform atrocities.&quot;<br><br>
All enemies are dehumanized in any conflict. This is what makes it possible for people to kill the enemy in combat, and win. It is a very primal game, an archetype of humanity that is invariant across all boundaries. I killed the enemy because I was not killing another human being. The enemy killed us because to him we were not human either. That should not surprise anyone.<br><br>
I never regarded the Vietnamese people as lesser human beings. They are a gracious people with a long history. The enemy, Charlie, gooks, VC, etc., was the inhuman beast, the animal to be hunted and destroyed. There is a difference.<br><br>
I am very perplexed on how one considers and performs atrocities. Please define your concept of &quot;atrocity&quot;.
